.TH "NAVIGATION.ENTRIES" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Navigation.entries \- Navigation: entries() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]entries()\f[B]\f[R] method of the \f[CR]Navigation\f[R]
interface returns an array of \f[CR]NavigationHistoryEntry\f[R] objects
representing all existing history entries.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
entries()
.EE
.SS Parameters
None.
.SS Return value
An array of \f[CR]NavigationHistoryEntry\f[R] objects.
.SS Exceptions
None.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Return the number of entries in the history
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] numOfEntries = navigation.entries().length \- 1;
.EE
.SS A smart back button
A page\-supplied \(lqback\(rq button can take you back, even after
reload, by inspecting the previous history entries:
.IP
.EX
backButtonEl.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (
    navigation.entries()[navigation.currentEntry.index \- 1]?.url ===
    \(dq/product\-listing\(dq
  ) {
    navigation.back();
  } \f[B]else\f[R] {
    \f[I]// If the user arrived here in some other way\f[R]
    \f[I]// e.g. by typing the URL directly:\f[R]
    navigation.navigate(\(dq/product\-listing\(dq, { history: \(dqreplace\(dq });
  }
});
.EE
